included.description: My dissertation is titled "Involving Older Adults in the Design and Development of Free/Open Source Software" and includes a report of 4 research studies that I ran with older adults. Everyone deserves a say in our technology revolution. 

I work toward that life slogan every day. A strong focus on treating users as the humans they are, and enabling a diversity of voices to be heard are ways to get there. included.name: Coping with Duplicate Bug Reports in Free/Open Source Software (FOSS) projects
included.publisher: Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE)
included.description: Free/Open Source Software (FOSS) communities often use open bug reporting to allow users to participate by reporting bugs. This practice can lead to more duplicate reports, as users can be less rigorous about researching existing bug reports. This paper examines how FOSS projects deal with duplicate bug reports. We examined 12 FOSS projects: 4 small, 4 medium and 4 large, where size was determined by number of code contributors. First, we found that contrary to what has been reported from studies of individual large projects like Mozilla and Eclipse, duplicate bug reports are a problem for FOSS projects, especially medium-sized, which struggle with a large number of submissions without the resources of large projects. Second, we found that the focus of a project does not affect the number of duplicate bug reports. Our findings indicate a need for additional scaffolding and training for bug reporters.

included.name: On Older Adults and Free/Open Source Software: Reflections of Older Contributors and Community Leaders
included.publisher: Proceedings of the IEEE Symposium on Visual Languages and Human-Centric Computing (VL/HCC 2014), Melbourne, Australia, 2014.
included.description: This paper reports on a set of well-designed interviews centered around the perceptions and activities of older people (50 years or older) in free/open source software communities (FOSS). One of the main findings is that older people experienced more social problems than technical problems in participation to recent projects. This result is important and worth further investigation for its confirmation and its causes.

included.name: Older Adults and Free/Open Source Software: A Diary Study of First-Time Contributors
included.publisher: In Proceedings of the 10th International Symposium on Open Collaboration (OpenSym 2014). ACM Press, 2014.
included.description: The paper reports on a diary study where adults aged 50 years and older were introduced to the open source community and were asked to contribute to the community in any form they wished to. These contributions were recorded and analyzed to understand the benefits and barriers from and to the community with respect to older adults.
